  "signature": "ed25519:b7d3e1a4c9f2b0e5d8a3c6f1b4e7a0d2c5f8b1e4a7d0c3f6b9e2a5d8c1f4b7e0",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA plan documented, version control enforced, regression test suite covering hemolysis transport solver passes at each release.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver is maintained under a formal SQA plan compliant with FDA guidance on software of unknown provenance. Version-controlled source repository with tagged release history is available. A regression test suite of 47 cases including hemolysis transport benchmarks is executed at each release and all tests pass. Documentation of SQA activities was reviewed and found complete for MRL 5 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the hemolysis transport equation; observed order of accuracy within 10% of theoretical order.",
      "rationale": "MMS was applied to the scalar hemolysis transport equation implemented in the solver. Observed spatial order of accuracy was 1.94 against a theoretical order of 2.0 for the second-order upwind scheme, a deviation of 3%, well within the 10% acceptance threshold. Temporal convergence was verified separately using a sinusoidal forcing function. Code verification is considered complete at the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for hemolysis index QoI on at least three systematically refined meshes; refinement ratio >= 1.3.",
      "rationale": "Three meshes with refinement ratio 1.35 were generated (4.2 M, 7.7 M, and 14.1 M cells). Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 1.8% and 2.1% for the fine-to-medium and medium-to-coarse pairs respectively, both below the 5% threshold. Asymptotic range check confirmed p_observed / p_theoretical = 0.97, indicating the solution is in the asymptotic range. Discretization error is adequately quantified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, hematocrit) documented with measurement uncertainty for all validation test points.",
      "rationale": "All five validation operating points were conducted using a calibrated mock circulatory loop. Inlet flow rates were measured with a Coriolis flowmeter (±0.5% reading), rotational speed with an optical tachometer (±0.1 RPM), fluid temperature with a calibrated thermocouple (±0.3 °C), and hematocrit with a microhematocrit centrifuge (±1%). Measurement uncertainty was propagated into the validation comparison using a first-order Taylor series expansion. Test condition documentation meets MRL 5 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative validation metric (e.g., E_rel) computed with combined simulation and experimental uncertainty; metric value within acceptance band at all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Relative error E_rel = (CFD - Exp) / Exp was computed at all five operating points. Values ranged from -4.1% to +6.8%, all within the ±10% acceptance band established by the clinical risk analysis. Combined standard uncertainty (simulation UQ + experimental measurement uncertainty) was included in the comparison following ASME V&V 20 methodology. The validation comparison is judged to meet the required level for MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Hemolysis index (HI) is the primary QoI used in both validation experiments and clinical submission; direct correspondence demonstrated.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) computed from the CFD scalar transport model maps directly to the NIH measured in the bench experiments using the modified Heuser-Opitz power-law model. The clinical submission threshold is expressed in the same units. No intermediate transformation or surrogate QoI is required. Relevance of QoI is fully established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on the same FDA generic pump geometry at operating conditions spanning the COU envelope; no extrapolation beyond validated range.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry — the identical geometry used in the COU simulations. The five operating points bracket the full clinical operating envelope (flow 2–8 L/min, speed 2000–3500 RPM). No extrapolation beyond the validated range is required for the COU predictions. Validation activity relevance is rated as meeting the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated to at least 5 orders of magnitude reduction in residuals for all governing equations; mass imbalance < 0.01%.",
      "rationale": "All simulations were run to 6-order residual reduction for continuity, momentum, and scalar transport equations. Mass imbalance across the impeller domain was < 0.003% in all cases. Double-precision arithmetic is used throughout. Solver error is considered negligible relative to other uncertainty sources and meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by independent analyst; checklist of COU-specific parameters (boundary conditions, turbulence model, hemolysis model coefficients) verified against approved simulation plan.",
      "rationale": "An independent CFD analyst reviewed the simulation setup against the approved simulation plan prior to production runs. A 34-item checklist covering boundary condition assignment, turbulence model selection (SST k-ω), wall treatment, hemolysis model coefficients, and post-processing scripts was completed and signed off. No discrepancies were identified. Use error controls are adequate for MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model and hemolysis power-law model selection justified by literature survey and sensitivity analysis; model form uncertainty quantified.",
      "rationale": "A literature survey of 12 published CFD hemolysis studies identified SST k-ω as the most consistently validated turbulence model for rotary blood pump flows. Sensitivity analysis comparing SST k-ω, realizable k-ε, and RSM showed hemolysis index differences of < 8% across models, which is within the experimental uncertainty band. Hemolysis power-law exponents (α = 3.62 × 10⁻⁵, β = 2.416, γ = 0.785) were taken from the Giersiepen et al. calibration dataset and their uncertainty was propagated via Monte Carlo. Model form uncertainty is adequately characterized."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters identified; uncertainty distributions assigned and propagated via Monte Carlo (N >= 5000 samples); sensitivity indices computed.",
      "rationale": "Fourteen model input parameters were identified including fluid viscosity, density, hematocrit, hemolysis model exponents, and inlet velocity profile shape. Uncertainty distributions were assigned based on experimental calibration data and literature. A Monte Carlo analysis with 10 000 samples was performed. Sobol sensitivity indices identified hemolysis exponent β and hematocrit as the dominant contributors (combined 74% of output variance). Input uncertainty is fully characterized at the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Biological replicates from at least three independent blood donors per operating point; inter-donor variability characterized and reported as part of experimental uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis experiments were conducted using blood samples from two independent donors per operating point, with three technical replicates per donor (six measurements total per point). The assessment team acknowledges that the required level specifies a minimum of three independent biological donors to adequately characterize inter-donor variability at MRL 5. However, the coefficient of variation across donors was low (mean CV = 4.2%), and the two-donor dataset is consistent with published FDA pump hemolysis benchmarks that used comparable sample sizes. Expert panel consensus, drawing on prior experience with five similar rotary pump assessments, concluded that the observed inter-donor consistency provides sufficient confidence that a third donor would not materially alter the uncertainty characterization. The Monte Carlo UQ framework conservatively inflates the experimental uncertainty component by a factor of 1.4 to partially compensate for the reduced donor count. On balance, the panel judged the evidence adequate to support an Accepted outcome at the package level, treating the two-donor limitation as a documented residual uncertainty rather than a disqualifying gap."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters (fluid properties, operating conditions) demonstrated to match experimental conditions within stated measurement uncertainty at each validation point.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was constructed for each of the five operating points, comparing CFD inputs to experimentally measured values. All parameters were within one combined standard uncertainty of the experimental measurements. Fluid viscosity was matched to within 0.8% using temperature-controlled bovine blood analogue. Rotational speed boundary condition matched tachometer reading to within 0.05%. Equivalency is fully demonstrated."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-hemolysis-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-panel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment panel reviewed all 13 credibility factors for COU2 (VAD hemolysis prediction, MRL 5). Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required levels. The single shortfall — Test samples achieving Level 2 against a required Level 3 — was reviewed in detail. The panel noted that (1) inter-donor CV across the two donors was 4.2%, well below the 10% threshold typically associated with donor-to-donor variability in bovine blood hemolysis studies; (2) the Monte Carlo UQ framework applies a conservative 1.4× inflation factor to experimental uncertainty to partially compensate for the reduced biological replicate count; (3) the assessment team has completed five prior rotary pump credibility assessments using two-donor datasets and in each case subsequent three-donor studies confirmed the hemolysis estimates within the original uncertainty bounds; and (4) the output comparison factor — rated at Level 4, one level above its requirement — provides additional confidence that the model-to-experiment agreement is robust across the operating envelope. Taken together, the panel concluded by consensus that the aggregate evidence base is sufficient to support clinical submission and that the two-donor limitation does not introduce unacceptable risk given the conservative UQ treatment. Decision: Accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
